         =20
            <p><strong>Story by Peter&nbsp;Krause</strong></p>

<p>Improving lap times when self-coaching is kind of like eating an elephan=
t. You have to start small. Without a detailed plan, that goal is going to =
be really hard to&nbsp;achieve.</p>

<p>There you are, watching a replay of an entire lap for clues or comparing=
 your own squiggly lines with ones from equally inconsistent friends in the=
 paddock. Where to start? What to&nbsp;do?</p>

<p>Drivers sometimes =E2=80=9Csend it=E2=80=9D in an effort to change somet=
hing=E2=80=93<em>anything</em>. In the process, they blow past the desired =
risk-benefit ratio and bad things can happen. It doesn=E2=80=99t have to be=
 that&nbsp;way.</p>

<p>What=E2=80=99s my advice as a seasoned, professional coach for bootstrap=
ping your performance? First, narrow your focus to a few goals we always tr=
y to achieve. Strive for the best execution of fundamental skills. Use all =
the width of the road=E2=80=93unless there is a compelling reason not to. C=
ommit to maximum throttle, and brake whenever the wheel is straight or near=
ly&nbsp;so.</p>

<p>Second, avoid the most common pitfalls. Don=E2=80=99t come away from the=
 outside edge of the road too soon for a corner. Yet don=E2=80=99t drive so=
 deep or square off the corner so much that you run the risk of missing the=
 apex&nbsp;area.</p>

<p><span class=3D"dquo">=E2=80=9C</span>How do you eat an elephant?=E2=80=
=9D asks my friend and colleague Ross Bentley. =E2=80=9COne bite at a time,=
=E2=80=9D is my reliable&nbsp;answer.</p>
         =20

           =20

            <div class=3D"">
            <!-- Sidebar sections -->
           =20
           =20
               =20
                <h3>Let=E2=80=99s Go to Sebring</h3>
               =20
                   =20
               =20
                <p>So, for a popular hypothetical, let=E2=80=99s go faster =
at Sebring. Let=E2=80=99s start with one small, three-bend area of the trac=
k that is crucial to a good lap=E2=80=93and to do it right, all the fundame=
ntal skills are important.</p>

<p>We=E2=80=99re looking at Sebring=E2=80=99s Turn 3-4-5 complex. Why this =
section? Thirty-plus years of experience working with hundreds of drivers, =
bolstered by measuring segment times=E2=80=93first with a stopwatch, then w=
ith data=E2=80=93has shown that drivers often lose more than they can gain =
here by simply being inconsistent.</p>

<div data-oembed-url=3D"https://youtu.be/J4QlN9ZlTcY">
<div style=3D"height:0; left:0; padding-bottom:56.25%; position:relative; w=
idth:100%"><iframe allow=3D"accelerometer; clipboard-write; encrypted-media=
; gyroscope; picture-in-picture;" allowfullscreen=3D"" scrolling=3D"no" src=
=3D"cid:frame-4977C759C23829FCA86EBD583DFEDCC6@mhtml.blink" style=3D"top: 0=
; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; position: absolute; border: 0;"></ifr=
ame></div>
</div>

<p><br>
This complex requires, as a proportion of the whole lap, a lot more time to=
 negotiate. Hence, it=E2=80=99s easier to =E2=80=9Cmine time=E2=80=9D here =
for greater improvement.&nbsp;</p>

<p>How much improvement? As much a full second for those in the 2:10-to-2:2=
0 lap time range, and more for those running between 2:20 and 2:40. You can=
=E2=80=99t get that benefit in single corners=E2=80=93even Turn 1 or the ha=
irpin. You=E2=80=99re simply not in them long enough.</p>

<p>The bigger picture: Fixing just one small section of track=E2=80=93any t=
rack=E2=80=93can pay huge dividends. How much would you pay for that 1-seco=
nd gain? Exactly.</p>

<p><img height=3D"662" src=3D"https://s3.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/prod.mm.co=
m/uploads/2022/09/06/1662492819_screen-shot-2022-09-06-at-32224-pm_mmthumb.=
png" width=3D"1148"></p>

<p><strong>A. </strong>First, make an extremely detailed plan for where you=
=E2=80=99re going to put the car=E2=80=93not just at points, but ahead in t=
he complex. Braking for Turn 3 is from high speed, requiring downshifting l=
ater in the brake zone, and drivers should make sure the right side of the =
car is parallel with the right side of the road and no more than a half a c=
ar width away from the right edge.</p>

<p><strong>B. </strong>Think positively instead of negatively. Instead of a=
nxiety over establishing an initial braking point, focus on defining an =E2=
=80=9Caccelerate to here=E2=80=9D point=E2=80=93say, the far side of the se=
cond access road on the right when approaching the brake zone for Turn 3. T=
his makes wide-open throttle last longer and also makes the braking more ef=
ficient=E2=80=93because it has to be!</p>

<p><strong>C.</strong> The cleanliness of 100% throttle to max deceleration=
 is a best execution of a fundamental skill. You=E2=80=99re looking for fro=
nt-load peak deceleration earlier rather than later in the brake zone. This=
 gives you more options later as you enter the corner.</p>

<p><strong>D.</strong> Discipline yourself to leave enough brake for the co=
rner by concentrating on earlier and slower brake release=E2=80=93even exte=
nding past the initial steering input. This allows you to roll a little mor=
e speed into the corner and also allows the brake zone to extend into corne=
r entry. The goal should be to wrap the car around the corner, coming close=
 to only the last few car lengths of apex curb.</p>

<p><strong>E. </strong>At the Turn 3 apex, take only as much curb as requir=
ed to avoid unsettling the car or requiring any correction or hesitation to=
 get back to wide-open throttle for the bend to the right through Turn 4. I=
f you=E2=80=99re against the Turn 3 apex curb before the last few panels, y=
ou=E2=80=99re turning in early, too quickly or both.</p>

<p><strong>F.</strong> When it becomes remotely clear that you=E2=80=99re g=
oing to make it to the Turn 3 apex curb=E2=80=93or at least very, very clos=
e to it=E2=80=93commit to big throttle and get the car accelerating again. =
Cover the distance from back to throttle to the next speed adjustment downw=
ard=E2=80=93either braking for quicker cars or breathing throttle for slowe=
r cars=E2=80=93to get to Turn 5 as quickly as possible.</p>

<p><strong>G. </strong>It=E2=80=99s shocking how many drivers dillydally, m=
eander and lollygag while traveling between Turns 3 and 5. Every moment cou=
nts. Drive like it.</p>

<p><strong>H.</strong> Now comes the hard part, the greatest challenge of t=
his complex. The Turn 5 entry should begin center or right of center, blend=
ing and extending the end of braking into turn entry and past steering whee=
l input to the left. This makes for an easier apex two-thirds of the way ar=
ound the inside curbing. By doing this, completion to wide-open throttle al=
lows the car to slide out parallel to the exit curb past half distance of t=
he curb. The whole goal for Turn 5 is to be faster in, slower earlier and f=
or as short a distance as possible, and then back to wide-open throttle soo=
ner and without any throttle correction.</p>
               =20
           =20
               =20
                <h3>Seeing the Speed</h3>
               =20
                   =20
               =20
                <p><img height=3D"780" src=3D"https://s3.us-east-2.amazonaw=
s.com/prod.mm.com/uploads/2022/09/06/1662493178_2020_01_1117_14_497857_mmth=
umb.JPG" width=3D"1170"></p>

<p>The best drivers have the clearest vision of where they want to go and e=
xactly what they want to do when they get there. They=E2=80=99re able to co=
mmit and willing to tell the car how to move. To reach this level, start by=
 identifying and practicing proper car placement, then focus on maximizing =
throttle and brake commitment.&nbsp;</p>

<p>Pick small, slower-but-with-speed-change sections of track and summon ex=
tra concentration to attack them with vigor. VIR Turns 4-5-6, Road America =
Turns 12-13-14, Mosport Turns 9 and 10, and Summit Point Turns 5-6-7 are al=
so examples. If you have data, especially video with speed on it, use these=
 tools to validate what you=E2=80=99re doing. Add speed gradually and, most=
 of all, enjoy the benefits of your newfound commitment, which will yield d=
esired performance improvement.&nbsp;</p>

<p><em>Peter Krause, a longtime driver coach, operates<a href=3D"https://pe=
terkrause.net/Krause_%26_Associates_LLC/Welcome.html" target=3D"_blank"> Kr=
ause &amp; Associates LLC</a>.</em></p>
               =20
           =20
               =20
           =20
               =20
           =20
           =20
            </div>


          <!-- Side bars -->
         =20
         =20
           =20
         =20
           =20
         =20
           =20
              <div class=3D"sidebar block">
              <h3>Fundamentals of Speed</h3>
             =20
               =20
             =20
                <div class=3D"content">
                  <p><img height=3D"780" src=3D"https://s3.us-east-2.amazon=
aws.com/prod.mm.com/uploads/2022/09/06/1662493636_2020_01_1108_40_429786_mm=
thumb.JPG" width=3D"1170"></p>

<p>An easy way to find speed involves simply finding the lowest-hanging fru=
it. Fire up your in-car video and watch your performance through longer, sl=
ower, critical corners.</p>

<p>Note your slowest speed in the corner (vMin) and add 2 or 3 mph.&nbsp;</=
p>

<p>Now count off the seconds: If you could just end slowing later and pick =
up speed earlier from vMin, how much could you raise your average speed thr=
ough that slower corner?</p>

<p>You can=E2=80=99t get rid of all the time dillydallying around vMin, but=
 you can work to shorten the huge hit on average speed through the corner b=
y ending braking later, closer to the apex, and completing the progression =
to wide-open throttle just a little earlier.</p>

<p>The givens are universal. Achieve these first. Place the car accurately =
and consistently laterally for every foot covered on the track. Use landmar=
ks at track level (curbs, cracks, seams, patches), eye level (corner statio=
ns, tire wall edges, guardrails) and above (PA speakers, light poles, billb=
oards, bridges) so you can form a =E2=80=9Csight picture=E2=80=9D of how th=
ese are all in alignment to mark your progress around the track: turn-in, a=
pex and exit.&nbsp;</p>

<p>This sounds basic, but when you=E2=80=99re pushing incrementally, it=E2=
=80=99ll also keep you safer. If you=E2=80=99re not in the right place, the=
n you=E2=80=99ll know that you can bail if you overcook it.&nbsp;</p>

<p>Hone your go/no-go system=E2=80=93thanks to Ron Zitza for this great pea=
rl of wisdom. If you=E2=80=99re good, go! If something is not right=E2=80=
=93did going wide at the previous exit put you out of position for the next=
 corner?=E2=80=93then no-go to the next driver input. Settle the car down a=
nd attack next time around.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
           =20
         =20
           =20
              <div class=3D"sidebar block">
              <h3>Two for One: How Improving One Part of Track Benefits Oth=
ers</h3>
             =20
               =20
             =20
                <div class=3D"content">
                  <p><img height=3D"832" src=3D"https://s3.us-east-2.amazon=
aws.com/prod.mm.com/uploads/2022/09/06/1662492931_screen-shot-2022-09-06-at=
-32236-pm_mmthumb.png" width=3D"758"></p>

<p>A simple benefit to learning how to best negotiate a section of track: Y=
ou can apply those skills to other turns.</p>

<p>Sticking with Sebring, most of the goals for Turns 3-4-5 will come in ha=
ndy at another extremely similar complex: Turns 15 and 16. (Flip over the l=
atter to see the former.)</p>

<p>By studying and practicing Turns 3-4-5, you can execute and commit bette=
r through the 15-16 complex while optimizing the crucial exit onto the back=
 straight. That=E2=80=99s more than double the benefit.</p>

<p>From brake application for Turn 3 to track-out at Turn 5, a driver doing=
 a 2:15 lap time is in this section for 16.5 seconds. They=E2=80=99re in Tu=
rns 15 and 16 for 13.5 seconds. Combined, that=E2=80=99s 30 seconds, more t=
han 22% of their entire lap time. Sure, of course you can practice and impr=
ove individual corners, but for the return on the time and effort expended,=
 this kind of exercise is where most people gain the most time=E2=80=93and =
it applies to any track.&nbsp;</p>

<p>Every driver needs to look at specific skill executions required and thi=
nk of other corners at other tracks that are similar in geometry or overall=
 approach. Many of the goals for this area of the track can make driving si=
milar corners at other tracks better, simply because the driver now knows h=
ow to look for solutions. The process is the same, no matter what track or =
car you happen to drive.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
